  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Corruption Watch - Local Language Version</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">This means that the likelihood of exposure must increase, same as investigations, prosecution, payback, policy change and prevention. Corruption is always guided by the 5Ps. Sustained effort on these issues disseminated widely to Ghanaians we believe will motivate them to join the fight against corruption and for authorities to act
&#x2022; Another important strategy is to invest in social media platforms to reinforce the message from radio and TV. This has proved effective so far</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">&#x2022;	Increased responsiveness of both state institutions cited in the corruption cases that will be highlighted and anticorruption institutions with a mandate to fight corruption. The project hopes that by keeping the spotlight on these cases, these institutions will be forced to act. This responsiveness will be measured in the increased number of investigations, enquires, prosecutions, administrative sanctions, recovery of stolen resources and policy change. These results may or may not be initiated solely by the Corruption Watch team but may be tracked and given visibility and lead to the results.
&#x2022;	The project expects to sustain media focus on corruption.
&#x2022;	Also, the project expects to incentivize anti-corruption &#x2013;related behavioural change among public officers and citizen
&#x2022;	Lastly, the project expects to achieve an increase in the number of citizens that have been educated about corruption through local language, particularly Asante Twi.</narrative>
  </description>
